  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 6
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 6
  levelTerms:
  - level: 23
    terms:
    - term: Rotation
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Spinning movement of an object without leaving its actual position
      details: The spinning movement of an object without actually leaving its position,
        kind of like how a top spins as it is being unwind by the rope, or how our
        planet has night and day.
    - term: Revolution
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Movement of object around the axis of a point or another object
      details: 'The other hand, is the movement of an object around the axis. This
        means that object is said to be revolving if it is moving around a point,
        or axis, while an object is said to be rotating if it

        spins in its
        place.'
    - term: 'Angular Position '
      unit: "\u03B8"
      type: 0
      description: "One full rotation is 360\xB0 in degrees or 2\u03C0 rads in radians"
      details: "Before, our Position is denoted by \U0001D451, and this is usually
        associated with linear motion. But, it is also applicable to circles, and
        even rotational motion. Here, it denotes the orientation of a rotating object
        in free space. It also represents the direction of the displacement vector
        drawn from the origin (or axis) to the location of the revolving object."
    - term: 'Angular Displacement '
      unit: "\u0394\u03B8"
      type: 0
      description: Similar to linear displacement, where an angle has rotated in
        a specified direction and axis
      details: It is the measurement where the angle through which a point, line,
        or body has rotated in a specified direction, about a specified axis.
    - term: 'Angular Velocity '
      unit: w
      type: 0
      description: Rate of change in object's angular displacement over time
      details: "Just like the linear velocity, angular velocity also shows the rate
        of change in an object\u2019s position. What differs from the linear velocity
        is that it measures the change in object\u2019s angular displacement per
        unit of time"
    - term: 'Angular Acceleration '
      unit: a
      type: 0
      description: Rate of change in angular velocity
      details: This is also similar with the rectilinear acceleration, only this
        time, it involves angular velocity. Also, a is a vector. Its value is dependent
        on the direction it takes. In this case, if w is going in a different direction
        than a, then w is negative. Likewise, if w follows a, then w is positive.
  - level: 24
    terms:
    - term: Moment of Inertia
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Also called rotational inertia. It is dependent on mass and position
        of the object's axis
      details: "It is dependent on both mass and the position of the object\u2019s
        axis. The axis can exist anywhere from within the object itself or outside
        its system. The moment of inertia changes because of the changes in position
        its axis is placed at. By definition, rotational inertia is the resistance
        of a rotating body to change its current state of balance, which in this
        case, is its rotation."
    - term: Torque
      unit: "\u03C4"
      type: 2
      description: It is rotational counterpart of linear force
      details: "Imagine that moment when you pushed the door too hard, it swung open
        very rapidly. You just saw the door swung past youvery fast, then hit the
        wall with a very loud, \u201CTHUD!\u201D That door has just experienced torque.\n\nTorque:
        \u03C4 = i\u03B1\ni = moment of inertia, \u03B1 = angular acceleration"
    - term: Angular Momentum
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: It is rotational counterpart of linear momentum
      details: This implies that larger masses have bigger momenta than smaller bodies.
        Likewise, having a faster angular velocity also lends its hand in increasing
        angular momentum. When ever we push a round table, ride the bike, or even
        just open the door, we all exert torque. If the torque we exert is stronger
        than the other torques opposing the torque we exert, then the object rotates,
        such as the strong slam of the door if we open it with a great heave. So,
        the greater the net torque exerted within a short time, the stronger the
        angular momentum, which is shown mathematically,
    - term: Angular Work
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Work done by a rotating system
      details: Rotational motion also performs work and has kinetic energy and momentum.
        however, translates work within a certain angular displacement in which it
        is known as the arc length (usually stylized as the symbol S). Arc length
        is defined by the formula,
